# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: secure-firmware-update
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:secure-firmware-update/chain-of-trust] In computer security, a **chain of trust** is established by validating each component of hardware and software from the end entity up to the root certificate.
[src:secure-firmware-update/chain-of-trust] It is intended to ensure that only trusted software and hardware can be used while still retaining flexibility.
[src:secure-firmware-update/chain-of-trust] A chain of trust is designed to allow multiple users to create and use the software on the system, which would be more difficult if all the keys were stored directly in hardware.
[src:secure-firmware-update/chain-of-trust] It starts with hardware that will only boot from software that is digitally signed (bootloader).
[src:secure-firmware-update/chain-of-trust] The signing authority will only sign boot programs that enforce security, such as only running programs that are themselves signed, or only allowing signed code to have access to certain features of the machine.
[src:secure-firmware-update/chain-of-trust] This process may continue for several layers.
[src:secure-firmware-update/chain-of-trust] This process results in a chain of trust.
[src:secure-firmware-update/chain-of-trust] The final software can be trusted to have certain properties because if it had been illegally modified its signature would be invalid, and the previous software would not have executed it.
[src:secure-firmware-update/chain-of-trust] The previous software can be trusted, because it, in turn, would not have been loaded if its signature had been invalid.
[src:secure-firmware-update/chain-of-trust] The trustworthiness of each layer is guaranteed by the one before, back to the trust anchor.
[src:secure-firmware-update/chain-of-trust] It would be possible to have the hardware check the suitability (signature) for every single piece of software.
[src:secure-firmware-update/chain-of-trust] However, this would not produce the flexibility that a "chain" provides.
[src:secure-firmware-update/chain-of-trust] In a chain, any given link can be replaced with a different version to provide different properties, without having to go all the way back to the trust anchor.
[src:secure-firmware-update/chain-of-trust] This use of multiple layers is an application of a general technique to improve scalability and is analogous to the use of multiple certificates in a certificate chain.
[src:secure-firmware-update/chain-of-trust] In computer security, digital certificates are verified using a chain of trust.
[src:secure-firmware-update/chain-of-trust] The trust anchor for the digital certificate is the root certificate authority (CA).
[src:secure-firmware-update/chain-of-trust] The certificate hierarchy is a structure of certificates that allows individuals to verify the validity of a certificate's issuer.
[src:secure-firmware-update/chain-of-trust] Certificates are issued and signed by certificates that reside higher in the certificate hierarchy, so the validity and trustworthiness of a given certificate is determined by the corresponding validity of the certificate that signed it.
[src:secure-firmware-update/chain-of-trust] The chain of trust of a certificate chain is an ordered list of certificates, containing an end-user subscriber certificate and intermediate certificates (that represents the intermediate CA), that enables the receiver to verify that the sender and all intermediate certificates are trustworthy.
[src:secure-firmware-update/chain-of-trust] This process is best described in the page *Intermediate certificate authority*.
[src:secure-firmware-update/chain-of-trust] See also X.509 certificate chains for a description of these concepts in a widely used standard for digital certificates.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] Code signing can provide several valuable features.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] The most common use of code signing is to provide security when deploying; in some programming languages, it can also be used to help prevent namespace conflicts.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] Almost every code signing implementation will provide some sort of digital signature mechanism to verify the identity of the author or build system, and a checksum to verify that the object has not been modified.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] It can also be used to provide versioning information about an object or to store other metadata about an object.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] The efficacy of code signing as an authentication mechanism for software depends on the security of underpinning signing keys.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] As with other public key infrastructure (PKI) technologies, the integrity of the system relies on publishers securing their private keys against unauthorized access.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] Keys stored in software on general-purpose computers are susceptible to compromise.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] Therefore, it is more secure, and best practice, to store keys in secure, tamper-proof, cryptographic hardware devices known as hardware security modules or HSMs.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] Many code signing implementations will provide a way to sign the code using a system involving a pair of keys, one public and one private, similar to the process employed by TLS or SSH.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] For example, in the case of .NET, the developer uses a private key to sign their libraries or executables each time they build.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] This key will be unique to a developer or group or sometimes per application or object.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] The developer can either generate this key on their own or obtain one from a trusted certificate authority (CA).
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] Code signing is particularly valuable in distributed environments, where the source of a given piece of code may not be immediately evident - for example Java applets, ActiveX controls and other active web and browser scripting code.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] Another important usage is to safely provide updates and patches to existing software.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] Windows, Mac OS X, and most Linux distributions provide updates using code signing to ensure that it is not possible for others to maliciously distribute code via the patch system.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] It allows the receiving operating system to verify that the update is legitimate, even if the update was delivered by third parties or physical media (disks).
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] Code signing is used on Windows and Mac OS X to authenticate software on first run, ensuring that the software has not been maliciously tampered with by a third-party distributor or download site.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] Debian-based Linux distributions (among others) validate downloaded packages using public key cryptography.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] The public key used to authenticate the code signature should be traceable back to a trusted root authority CA, preferably using a secure public key infrastructure (PKI).
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] This does not ensure that the code itself can be trusted, only that it comes from the stated source (or more explicitly, from a particular private key).
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] A CA provides a root trust level and is able to assign trust to others by proxy.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] If a user trusts a CA, then the user can presumably trust the legitimacy of code that is signed with a key generated by that CA or one of its proxies.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] Many operating systems and frameworks contain built-in trust for one or more certification authorities.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] It is also commonplace for large organizations to implement a private CA, internal to the organization, which provides the same features as public CAs, but it is only trusted within the organization.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] Extended validation (EV) code signing certificates are subject to additional validation and technical requirements.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] These guidelines are based on the CA/B Forum's Baseline Requirements and Extended Validation Guidelines.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] Certain applications, such as signing Windows 10 kernel-mode drivers, require an EV code signing certificate.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] This is an example of a decoded EV code signing certificate used by SSL.com to sign software.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] `SSL.com EV Code Signing Intermediate CA RSA R3` is shown as the Issuer's commonName, identifying this as an EV code signing certificate.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] The certificate's `Subject` field describes SSL Corp as an organization.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] `Code Signing` is shown as the sole X509v3 Extended Key Usage.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] The other model is the trust on first use model, in which developers can choose to provide their own self-generated key.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] In this scenario, the user would normally have to obtain the public key in some fashion directly from the developer to verify the object is from them for the first time.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] Many code signing systems will store the public key inside the signature.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] Some software frameworks and OSs that check the code's signature before executing will allow you to choose to trust that developer from that point on after the first run.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] An application developer can provide a similar system by including the public keys with the installer.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] The key can then be used to ensure that any subsequent objects that need to run, such as upgrades, plugins, or another application, are all verified as coming from that same developer.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] Time-stamping was designed to circumvent the trust warning that will appear in the case of an expired certificate.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] In effect, time-stamping extends the code trust beyond the validity period of a certificate.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] In the event that a certificate has to be revoked due to a compromise, a specific date and time of the compromising event will become part of the revocation record.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] In this case, time-stamping helps establish whether the code was signed before or after the certificate was compromised.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] Developers need to sign their iOS and tvOS apps before running them on any real device and before uploading them to the App Store.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] This is needed to prove that the developer owns a valid Apple Developer ID.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] An application needs a valid profile or certificate so that it can run on the devices.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] Like any security measure, code signing can be defeated.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] Users can be tricked into running unsigned code, or even into running code that refuses to validate, and the system only remains secure as long as the private key remains private.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] It is also important to note that code signing does not protect the end user from any malicious activity or unintentional software bugs by the software author — it merely ensures that the software has not been modified by anyone other than the author.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] Sometimes, sandbox systems do not accept certificates, because of a false time-stamp or because of an excess usage of RAM.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] Microsoft implements a form of code signing (based on Authenticode) provided for Microsoft tested drivers.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] Since drivers run in the kernel, they can destabilize the system or open the system to security holes.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] For this reason, Microsoft tests drivers submitted to its WHQL program.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] After the driver has passed, Microsoft signs that version of the driver as being safe.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] On 32-bit systems only, installing drivers that are not validated with Microsoft is possible after agreeing to allow the installation at a prompt warning the user that the code is unsigned.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] For .NET (managed) code, there is an additional mechanism called Strong Name Signing that uses Public/Private keys and SHA-1 hash as opposed to certificates.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] However, Microsoft discourages reliance on Strong Name Signing as a replacement for Authenticode.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] The CAs subsequently issued announcements on compliance with the decision.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] In the context of consumer devices such as games consoles, the term "unsigned code" is often used to refer to an application which has not been signed with the cryptographic key normally required for software to be accepted and executed.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] Most console games have to be signed with a secret key designed by the console maker or the game will not load on the console (both to enforce Vendor lock-in and combat software piracy).
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] There are several methods to get unsigned code to execute which include software exploits, the use of a modchip, a technique known as the swap trick or running a softmod.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] It may not initially seem obvious why simply copying a signed application onto another DVD does not allow it to boot.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] On the Xbox, the reason for this is that the Xbox executable file (XBE) contains a media-type flag, which specifies the type of media that the XBE is bootable from.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] On nearly all Xbox software, this is set such that the executable will only boot from factory-produced discs, so simply copying the executable to burnable media is enough to stop the execution of the software.
[src:secure-firmware-update/code-signing] However, since the executable is signed, simply changing the value of the flag is not possible as this alters the signature of the executable, causing it to fail validation when checked.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] In computing, **firmware** (**FW**) is software that provides low-level control of computer hardware.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] For a relatively simple device, firmware may perform all control, monitoring and data manipulation functionality.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] For a more complex device, firmware may provide only relatively low-level control as well as hardware abstraction to higher-level software such as an operating system.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] Firmware is found in a wide range of computing devices, including personal computers, smartphones, home appliances, vehicles, computer peripherals and in many of the integrated circuits inside each of these larger systems.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] Firmware is stored in non-volatile memory – either read-only memory (ROM) or programmable memory such as EPROM, EEPROM, or flash.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] Changing a device's firmware stored in ROM requires physically replacing the memory chip or the device itself.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] Programmable firmware memory can be reprogrammed via a procedure sometimes called *flashing*.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] Common reasons for changing firmware include fixing bugs and adding features.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] Ascher Opler used the term *firmware* in a 1967 *Datamation* article, as an intermediary term between *hardware* and *software*.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] Opler projected that fourth-generation computer systems would have a writable control store (a small specialized high-speed memory) into which microcode firmware would be loaded.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] Many software functions would be moved to microcode, and instruction sets could be customized, with different firmware loaded for different instruction sets.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] As computers began to increase in complexity, it became clear that various programs needed to first be initiated and run to provide a consistent environment necessary for running more complex programs at the user's discretion.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] This required programming the computer to run those programs automatically.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] Furthermore, as companies, universities, and marketers wanted to sell computers to laypeople with little technical knowledge, greater automation became necessary to allow a layperson to easily run programs for practical purposes.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] This gave rise to a kind of software that a user would not consciously run, and it led to software that a lay user would not even know about.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] As originally used, firmware contrasted with hardware (the CPU itself) and software (normal instructions executing on a CPU).
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] It was not composed of CPU machine instructions, but of lower-level microcode involved in the implementation of machine instructions.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] It existed on the boundary between hardware and software; thus the name *firmware*.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] In some respects, the various firmware components are as important as the operating system in a working computer.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] However, unlike most modern operating systems, firmware rarely has a well-evolved automatic mechanism of updating itself to fix any functionality issues detected after shipping the unit.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] A computer's firmware may be manually updated by a user via a small utility program.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] In contrast, firmware in mass storage devices (hard-disk drives, optical disc drives, flash memory storage e.g., solid state drive) is less frequently updated, even when flash memory (rather than ROM, EEPROM) storage is used for the firmware.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] Most computer peripherals are themselves special-purpose computers.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] Devices such as printers, scanners, webcams, and USB flash drives have internally-stored firmware; some devices may also permit field upgrading of their firmware.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] For modern, simpler devices, such as USB keyboards, USB mouses and USB sound cards, the trend is to store the firmware in on-chip memory in the device's microcontroller, as opposed to storing it in a separate EEPROM chip.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] Consumer products like digital cameras and portable music players support firmware upgrades.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] In digital cameras, firmware upgrades address bugs in the operation, along with adding new functions to the camera's operation.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] Some companies use firmware updates to add new playable file formats (codecs).
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] Other features that may change with firmware updates include the user interface or even the battery life.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] Since 1996, most automobiles have employed an on-board computer and various sensors to detect mechanical problems.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] As of 2010, modern vehicles also employ computer-controlled anti-lock braking systems (ABS) and computer-operated transmission control units (TCUs).
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] The driver can also get in-dash information while driving in this manner, such as real-time fuel economy and tire pressure readings.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] Local dealers can update most vehicle firmware.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] Sometimes, third parties develop an unofficial new or modified ("aftermarket") version of firmware to provide new features or to unlock hidden functionality; this is referred to as custom firmware.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] An example is Rockbox as a firmware replacement for portable media players.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] There are many homebrew projects for various devices, which often unlock general-purpose computing functionality in previously limited devices (e.g., running Doom on iPods).
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] Firmware hacks usually take advantage of the firmware update facility on many devices to install or run themselves.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] Some, however, must resort to exploits to run, because the manufacturer has attempted to lock the hardware to stop it from running unlicensed code.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] Although the Kaspersky Lab report did not explicitly claim that this group is part of the United States National Security Agency (NSA), evidence obtained from the code of various Equation Group software suggests that they are part of the NSA.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] Researchers from the Kaspersky Lab categorized the undertakings by Equation Group as the most advanced hacking operation ever uncovered, also documenting around 500 infections caused by the Equation Group in at least 42 countries.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] Mark Shuttleworth, the founder of the company Canonical, which created the Ubuntu Linux distribution, has described proprietary firmware as a security risk, saying that "firmware on your device is the NSA's best friend" and calling firmware "a trojan horse of monumental proportions".
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] As a potential solution to this problem, he has called for declarative firmware, which would describe "hardware linkage and dependencies" and "should not include executable code".
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] Firmware should be open-source so that the code can be checked and verified.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] Custom firmware hacks have also focused on injecting malware into devices such as smartphones or USB devices.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] One such smartphone injection was demonstrated on the Symbian OS at MalCon, a hacker convention.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] A USB device firmware hack called BadUSB was presented at the Black Hat USA 2014 conference, demonstrating how a USB flash drive microcontroller can be reprogrammed to spoof various other device types to take control of a computer, exfiltrate data, or spy on the user.
[src:secure-firmware-update/firmware] Other security researchers have worked further on how to exploit the principles behind BadUSB, releasing at the same time the source code of hacking tools that can be used to modify the behavior of different USB devices.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] A **hardware security module** (**HSM**) is a physical computing device that safeguards and manages secrets (most importantly digital keys), and performs encryption and decryption functions for digital signatures, strong authentication and other cryptographic functions.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] These modules traditionally come in the form of a plug-in card or an external device that attaches directly to a computer or network server.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] A hardware security module contains one or more secure cryptoprocessor chips.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] HSMs may have features that provide tamper evidence such as visible signs of tampering or logging and alerting, or tamper resistance which makes tampering difficult without making the HSM inoperable, or tamper responsiveness such as deleting keys upon tamper detection.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] Each module contains one or more secure cryptoprocessor chips to prevent tampering and bus probing, or a combination of chips in a module that is protected by the tamper evident, tamper resistant, or tamper responsive packaging.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] A vast majority of existing HSMs are designed mainly to manage secret keys.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] Many HSM systems have means to securely back up the keys they handle outside of the HSM.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] Keys may be backed up in wrapped form and stored on a computer disk or other media, or externally using a secure portable device like a smartcard or some other security token.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] HSMs are used for real time authorization and authentication in critical infrastructure thus are typically engineered to support standard high availability models including clustering, automated failover, and redundant field-replaceable components.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] A few of the HSMs available in the market have the capability to execute specially developed modules within the HSM's secure enclosure.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] Such an ability is useful, for example, in cases where special algorithms or business logic has to be executed in a secured and controlled environment.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] The modules can be developed in native C language, .NET, Java, or other programming languages.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] Although the highest level of FIPS 140 security certification attainable is Security Level 4, most of the HSMs have Level 3 certification.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] In the Common Criteria system the highest EAL (Evaluation Assurance Level) is EAL7; most of the HSMs have EAL4+ certification.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] When used in financial payments applications, the security of an HSM is often validated against the HSM requirements defined by the Payment Card Industry Security Standards Council.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] A hardware security module can be employed in any application that uses digital keys.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] Typically, the keys would be of high value - meaning there would be a significant, negative impact to the owner of the key if it were compromised.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] HSMs are also deployed to manage transparent data encryption keys for databases and keys for storage devices such as disk or tape.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] Some HSM systems are also hardware cryptographic accelerators.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] They usually cannot beat the performance of hardware-only solutions for symmetric key operations.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] However, with performance ranges from 1 to 10,000 1024-bit RSA signatures per second, HSMs can provide significant CPU offload for asymmetric key operations.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] Since the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) is recommending the use of 2,048 bit RSA keys from year 2010, performance at longer key sizes has become more important.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] To address this issue, most HSMs now support elliptic curve cryptography (ECC), which delivers stronger encryption with shorter key lengths.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] In PKI environments, the HSMs may be used by certification authorities (CAs) and registration authorities (RAs) to generate, store, and handle asymmetric key pairs.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] On the other hand, device performance in a PKI environment is generally less important, in both online and offline operations, as Registration Authority procedures represent the performance bottleneck of the Infrastructure.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] Specialized HSMs are used in the payment card industry.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] HSMs support both general-purpose functions and specialized functions required to process transactions and comply with industry standards.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] They normally do not feature a standard API.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] The major organizations that produce and maintain standards for HSMs on the banking market are the Payment Card Industry Security Standards Council, ANS X9, and ISO.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] Performance-critical applications that have to use HTTPS (SSL/TLS), can benefit from the use of an SSL Acceleration HSM by moving the RSA operations, which typically requires several large integer multiplications, from the host CPU to the HSM device.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] Typical HSM devices can perform about 1 to 10,000 1024-bit RSA operations/second.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] Some performance at longer key sizes is becoming increasingly important.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] An increasing number of registries use HSMs to store the key material that is used to sign large zonefiles.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] OpenDNSSEC is an open-source tool that manages signing DNS zone files.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] On January 27, 2007, ICANN and Verisign, with support from the U.S.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] Department of Commerce, started deploying DNSSEC for DNS root zones.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] Root signature details can be found on the Root DNSSEC's website.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] Blockchain technology depends on cryptographic operations.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] Safeguarding private keys is essential to maintain the security of blockchain processes that utilize asymmetric cryptography.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] The private keys are often stored in a cryptocurrency wallet like the hardware wallet in the image.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] The synergy between HSMs and blockchain is mentioned in several papers, emphasizing their role in securing private keys and verifying identity, e.g. in contexts such as blockchain-driven mobility solutions.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] Automotive hardware security modules (HSMs) are embedded cryptographic coprocessors integrated into electronic control units (ECUs) to protect in-vehicle systems and communication buses against manipulation and misuse.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] They act as a hardware root of trust by securely generating and storing cryptographic keys and offloading security-critical operations such as secure boot, encryption, decryption, authentication and attestation.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] In modern ECU designs, HSMs are one of several hardware primitives that can underpin a hardware root of trust alongside secure elements, trusted platform modules (TPMs), one-time programmable (OTP) and read-only memories (ROM), and physical unclonable functions (PUFs).
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] Their use provides dedicated hardware support for cryptographic operations, but also introduces trade-offs in die area, power consumption and latency, so they are typically integrated into mid- and high-end automotive domain controllers rather than the smallest microcontrollers.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] Automotive HSMs are typically accompanied by dedicated firmware and software components that manage access to cryptographic services.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] These include HSM firmware, secure boot loaders, cryptographic libraries, and middleware that expose security services to the operating system and application software.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] In AUTOSAR-based systems, HSM firmware may interface with standardized service layers to provide cryptographic operations to applications.
[src:secure-firmware-update/hardware-security-module] Commercial HSM firmware implementations are available from several automotive software vendors, often as components integrated into AUTOSAR platforms or OEM security frameworks.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] A **patch** is data for modifying an existing software resource such as a program or a file, often to fix bugs and security vulnerabilities.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] To *patch* is also the process of applying the data to the existing resource.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Patching a system involves applying a patch.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] A patch may be created to improve functionality, usability, or performance.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] A patch may be created manually, but commonly it is created via a tool that compares two versions of the resource and generates data that can be used to transform one to the other.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Typically, a patch needs to be applied to the specific version of the resource it is intended to modify, although there are exceptions.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Some patching tools can detect the version of the existing resource and apply the appropriate patch, even if it supports multiple versions.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] As more patches are released, their cumulative size can grow significantly, sometimes exceeding the size of the resource itself.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] To manage this, the number of supported versions may be limited, or a complete copy of the resource might be provided instead.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Patching allows for modifying a binary executable.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Although this can be technically challenging (requires a thorough understanding of the workings of the executable), it may be feasible when the source code is unavailable to build a full executable, and it allows for a smaller distribution which can be more economical than distributing full files.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Although often intended to fix problems, a patch can introduce new problems – a scenario called software regression.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] In some cases, an update intentionally disables functionality, for instance, by removing aspects for which the consumer is no longer licensed.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Patch management is a part of lifecycle management, and involves a strategy and planning of what patches should be applied to which systems and at what times.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Typically, a patch is applied in a permanent way (i.e. to storage), but in some cases, a patch is applied to memory (i.e. via a tool such as a debugger) in which case the change is lost when the resource is reloaded from storage.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Software update is sometimes conflated with patch even though they are not synonyms.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] An update can be implemented using patch files and the patching process.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Also, some may contend that patching is not limited to modifying file content – that adding, removing and replacing whole files is patching.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Typically, patch connotates a relatively small change, so a patch that is large in size or scope may be called the more general *software update* or another more specific name such as service pack.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Windows NT and its successors (including Windows 2000, Windows XP, Windows Vista and Windows 7) use *service pack*.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Historically, IBM used the terms *FixPak* and *Corrective Service Diskette* for such updates.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Historically, software suppliers distributed patches on paper tape or on punched cards, expecting the recipient to cut out the indicated part of the original tape (or deck), and patch in (hence the name) the replacement segment.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Later patch distributions used magnetic tape.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Then, after the invention of removable disk drives, patches came from the software developer via a disk or, later, CD-ROM via mail.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] With widely available Internet access, downloading patches from the developer's web site or through automated software updates became often available to the end-users.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Starting with Apple's Mac OS 9 and Microsoft's Windows ME, PC operating systems gained the ability to get automatic software updates via the Internet.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Computer programs can often coordinate patches to update a target program.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Automation simplifies the end-user's task, allowing them to only execute an update program, whereupon that program makes sure that updating the target takes place completely and correctly.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Service packs for Microsoft Windows NT and its successors and for many commercial software products adopt such automated strategies.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Some programs can update themselves via the Internet with very little or no intervention on the part of users.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] The maintenance of server software and of operating systems often takes place in this manner.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] In situations where system administrators control a number of computers, this sort of automation helps to maintain consistency.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] The application of security patches commonly occurs in this manner.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] With the advent of larger storage media and higher Internet bandwidth, it became common to replace entire files (or even all of a program's files) rather than modifying existing files, especially for smaller programs.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Patches for proprietary software are typically distributed as executable files instead of source code.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] When executed these files load a program into memory which manages the installation of the patch code into the target program(s) on disk.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Patches for other software are typically distributed as data files containing the patch code.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] These are read by a patch utility program which performs the installation.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] This utility modifies the target program's executable file—the program's machine code—typically by overwriting its bytes with bytes representing the new patch code.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] If the new code will fit in the space (number of bytes) occupied by the old code, it may be put in place by overwriting directly over the old code.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] If the new code is bigger than the old code, the patch utility will append load record(s) containing the new code to the object file of the target program being patched.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] When the patched program is run, execution is directed to the new code with branch instructions (jumps or calls) patched over the place in the old code where the new code is needed.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] On early 8-bit microcomputers, for example the Radio Shack TRS-80, the operating system includes a PATCH/CMD utility which accepts patch data from a text file and applies the fixes to the target program's executable binary file(s).
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] The patch code must have place(s) in memory to be executed at runtime.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Inline patches are no difficulty, but when additional memory space is needed the programmer must improvise.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Naturally if the patch programmer is the one who first created the code to be patched, this is easier.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Savvy programmers plan in advance for this need by reserving memory for later expansion, left unused when producing their final iteration.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Other programmers not involved with the original implementation, seeking to incorporate changes at a later time, must find or make space for any additional bytes needed.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] The most fortunate possible circumstance for this is when the routine to be patched is a distinct module.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] In this case the patch programmer need merely adjust the pointers or length indicators that signal to other system components the space occupied by the module; he is then free to populate this memory space with his expanded patch code.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] If the routine to be patched does not exist as a distinct memory module, the programmer must find ways to shrink the routine to make enough room for the expanded patch code.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Small in-memory machine code patches can be manually applied with the system debug utility, such as CP/M's DDT or MS-DOS's DEBUG debuggers.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Programmers working in interpreted BASIC often used the POKE command to alter the functionality of a system service routine or the interpreter itself.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] A patch for source code defines how to modify the text of code files.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Such a patch is usually a text file that encodes the differences between two versions of a file.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] As this type of patch is often created via the `diff` command, the patch file is also a diff file.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Source code patching is common for an open-source software project.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] Maintainers receive patches or people publish patches that fix problems and add functionality, like support for local languages outside the project's locale.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] In an example from the early development of the Linux kernel (noted for publishing its complete source code), Linus Torvalds, the original author, received hundreds of thousands of patches from many programmers to apply against his original version.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] The Apache HTTP Server originally evolved as a number of patches that Brian Behlendorf collated to improve NCSA HTTPd, hence a name that implies that it is a collection of patches ("a patchy server").
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] The FAQ on the project's official site states that the name 'Apache' was chosen from respect for the Native American Indian tribe of Apache.
[src:secure-firmware-update/patch-computing] However, the 'a patchy server' explanation was initially given on the project's website.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] A **Trusted Platform Module** (**TPM**) is a secure cryptoprocessor that implements the **ISO/IEC 11889** standard.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] Common uses are verifying that the boot process starts from a trusted combination of hardware and software and storing disk encryption keys.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] A TPM 2.0 implementation is part of the Windows 11 system requirements.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] The first TPM version that was deployed was 1.1b in 2003.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] Trusted Platform Module (TPM) was conceived by a computer industry consortium called Trusted Computing Group (TCG).
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] It evolved into *TPM Main Specification Version 1.2* which was standardized by International Organization for Standardization (ISO) and International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) in 2009 as ISO/IEC 11889:2009.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] *TPM Main Specification Version 1.2* was finalized on 3 March 2011 completing its revision.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] On April 9, 2014, the Trusted Computing Group announced a major upgrade to their specification entitled *TPM Library Specification 2.0*.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] The group continues work on the standard incorporating errata, algorithmic additions and new commands, with its most recent edition published as 2.0 in November 2019.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] When a new revision is released, it is divided into multiple parts by the Trusted Computing Group.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] Each part consists of a document that makes up the whole of the new TPM specification.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] While TPM 2.0 addresses many of the same use cases and has similar features, the details are different.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] TPM 2.0 is not backward compatible with TPM 1.2.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] The TPM 2.0 policy authorization includes the 1.2 HMAC, locality, physical presence, and PCR.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] It adds authorization based on an asymmetric digital signature, indirection to another authorization secret, counters and time limits, NVRAM values, a particular command or command parameters, and physical presence.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] It permits the ANDing and ORing of these authorization primitives to construct complex authorization policies.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] Computer programs can use a TPM for the authentication of hardware devices, since each TPM chip has a unique and secret Endorsement Key (EK) burned in as it is produced.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] Security embedded in hardware provides more protection than a software-only solution.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] Its use is restricted in some countries.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] The primary scope of TPM is to ensure the integrity of a platform during boot time.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] In this context, "integrity" means "behaves as intended", and a "platform" is any computer device regardless of its operating system.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] This is to ensure that the boot process starts from a trusted combination of hardware and software, and continues until the operating system has fully booted and applications are running.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] When TPM is used, the firmware and the operating system are responsible for ensuring integrity.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] For example, the Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) can use TPM to form a root of trust: The TPM contains several Platform Configuration Registers (PCRs) that allow secure storage and reporting of security-relevant metrics.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] These metrics can be used to detect changes to previous configurations and decide how to proceed.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] Examples of such use can be found in Linux Unified Key Setup (LUKS), BitLocker and PrivateCore vCage memory encryption.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] Another example of platform integrity via TPM is in the use of Microsoft Office 365 licensing and Outlook Exchange.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] Another example of TPM use for platform integrity is the Trusted Execution Technology (TXT), which creates a chain of trust.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] It could remotely attest that a computer is using the specified hardware and software.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] Full disk encryption utilities, such as dm-crypt, can use this technology to protect the keys used to encrypt the computer's storage devices and provide integrity authentication for a trusted boot pathway that includes firmware and the boot sector.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] In 2006, new laptops began being sold with a built-in TPM chip.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] In the future, this concept could be co-located on an existing motherboard chip in computers, or any other device where the TPM facilities could be employed, such as a cellphone.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] On a PC, either the Low Pin Count (LPC) bus or the Serial Peripheral Interface (SPI) bus is used to connect to the TPM chip.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] The official TCG reference implementation of the TPM 2.0 Specification has been developed by Microsoft.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] It is licensed under BSD License and the source code is available on GitHub.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] In 2018, Intel open-sourced its Trusted Platform Module 2.0 (TPM2) software stack with support for Linux and Microsoft Windows.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] The source code is hosted on GitHub and licensed under BSD License.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] Infineon funded the development of an open source TPM middleware that complies with the Software Stack (TSS) Enhanced System API (ESAPI) specification of the TCG.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] It was developed by Fraunhofer Institute for Secure Information Technology (SIT).
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] IBM's Software TPM 2.0 is an implementation of the TCG TPM 2.0 specification.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] It is based on the TPM specification Parts 3 and 4 and source code donated by Microsoft.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] It contains additional files to complete the implementation.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] The source code is hosted on SourceForge and GitHub and licensed under BSD License.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] In 2022, AMD announced that under certain circumstances their fTPM implementation causes performance problems.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] A fix is available in form of a BIOS-Update.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] The Trusted Computing Group (TCG) has faced resistance to the deployment of this technology in some areas, where some authors see possible uses not specifically related to Trusted Computing, which may raise privacy concerns.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] The concerns include the abuse of remote validation of software to decide what software is allowed to run, and possible ways to follow actions taken by the user and record them in a database in a manner that is completely undetectable to the user.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] The TrueCrypt disk encryption utility, as well as its derivative VeraCrypt, do not support TPM.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] The original TrueCrypt developers were of the opinion that the exclusive purpose of the TPM is "to protect against attacks that require the attacker to have administrator privileges, or physical access to the computer".
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] The attacker who has physical or administrative access to a computer can circumvent TPM, e.g., by installing a hardware keystroke logger, by resetting TPM, or by capturing memory contents and retrieving TPM-issued keys.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] The condemning text goes so far as to claim that TPM is entirely redundant.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] The VeraCrypt publisher has reproduced the original allegation with no changes other than replacing "TrueCrypt" with "VeraCrypt".
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] The author is right that, after achieving either unrestricted physical access or administrative privileges, it is only a matter of time before other security measures in place are bypassed.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] However, stopping an attacker in possession of administrative privileges has never been one of the goals of TPM (see § Uses for details), and TPM can stop some physical tampering.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] In 2015, Richard Stallman suggested replacing the term "trusted computing" with the term "treacherous computing" due to the danger that the computer can be made to systematically disobey its owner if the cryptographical keys are kept secret from them.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] In August 2023, Linus Torvalds, who was frustrated with AMD fTPM's stuttering bugs, opined, "Let's just disable the stupid fTPM `hwrnd` thing." He said the CPU-based random number generation, `rdrand`, was equally suitable, despite having its share of bugs.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] In 2010, Christopher Tarnovsky presented an attack against TPMs at Black Hat Briefings, where he claimed to be able to extract secrets from a single TPM.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] He was able to do this after 6 months of work by inserting a probe and spying on an internal bus for the Infineon SLE 66 CL PC.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] In case of physical access, computers with TPM 1.2 are vulnerable to cold boot attacks as long as the system is on or can be booted without a passphrase from shutdown, sleep or hibernation, which is the default setup for Windows computers with BitLocker full disk encryption.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] A fix was proposed, which has been adopted in the specifications for TPM 2.0.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] In 2009, the concept of shared authorisation data in TPM 1.2 was found to be flawed.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] An adversary given access to the data could spoof responses from the TPM.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] In 2015, as part of the Snowden revelations, it was revealed that in 2010 a US CIA team claimed at an internal conference to have carried out a differential power analysis attack against TPMs that was able to extract secrets.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] Main Trusted Boot (tboot) distributions before November 2017 are affected by a dynamic root of trust for measurement (DRTM) attack CVE-2017-16837, which affects computers running on Intel's Trusted eXecution Technology (TXT) for the boot-up routine.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] In October 2017, it was reported that a code library developed by Infineon, which had been in widespread use in its TPMs, contained a vulnerability, known as ROCA, which generated weak RSA key pairs that allowed private keys to be inferred from public keys.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] As a result, all systems depending upon the privacy of such weak keys are vulnerable to compromise, such as identity theft or spoofing.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] Cryptosystems that store encryption keys directly in the TPM without blinding could be at particular risk to these types of attacks, as passwords and other factors would be meaningless if the attacks can extract encryption secrets.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] Infineon has released firmware updates for its TPMs to manufacturers who have used them.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] In 2018, a design flaw in the TPM 2.0 specification for the static root of trust for measurement (SRTM) was reported (CVE-2018-6622).
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] It allows an adversary to reset and forge platform configuration registers which are designed to securely hold measurements of software that are used for bootstrapping a computer.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] Fixing it requires hardware-specific firmware patches.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] An attacker abuses power interrupts and TPM state restores to trick TPM into thinking that it is running on non-tampered components.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] In 2021, the Dolos Group showed an attack on a discrete TPM, where the TPM chip itself had some tamper resistance, but the other endpoints of its communication bus did not.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] They read a full-disk-encryption key as it was transmitted across the motherboard, and used it to decrypt the laptop's SSD.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] As of 2025, a TPM is provided by nearly all PC and notebook manufacturers in their products.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] There are also hybrid types; for example, TPM can be integrated into an Ethernet controller, thus eliminating the need for a separate motherboard component.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] Field upgrade is the TCG term for updating the TPM firmware.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] The update can be between TPM 1.2 and TPM 2.0, or between firmware versions.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] Some vendors limit the number of transitions between 1.2 and 2.0, and some restrict rollback to previous versions.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] Platform OEMs such as HP supply an upgrade tool.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] Since July 28, 2016, all new Microsoft device models, lines, or series (or updating the hardware configuration of an existing model, line, or series with a major update, such as CPU, graphic cards) implement, and enable by default TPM 2.0.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] TPM endorsement keys (EKs) are asymmetric key pairs unique to each TPM.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] The TPM manufacturer usually provisions endorsement key certificates in TPM non-volatile memory.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] The certificates assert that the TPM is authentic.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] Starting with TPM 2.0, the certificates are in X.509 DER format.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] After the TPM was manufactured, the EKs cannot be changed.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] For fTPM, the EKs are stored on CPU / chipset when it was manufactured.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] These manufacturers typically provide their certificate authority root (and sometimes intermediate) certificates on their web sites.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] To utilize a TPM, the user needs a software library that communicates with the TPM and provides a friendlier API than the raw TPM communication.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] Currently, there are several such open-source TPM 2.0 libraries.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] Some of them also support TPM 1.2, but mostly TPM 1.2 chips are now deprecated and modern development is focused on TPM 2.0.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] Typically, a TPM library provides an API with one-to-one mappings to TPM commands.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] The TCG specification calls this layer the System API (SAPI).
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] This way, the user has more control over the TPM operations, but the complexity is high.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] To hide some of the complexity, most libraries also offer simpler ways to invoke complex TPM operations.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] The TCG specification call these two layers Enhanced System API (ESAPI) and Feature API (FAPI).
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] There is currently only one stack that follows the TCG specification.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] All the other available open-source TPM libraries use their own form of richer API.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] There is an application note about an example project for the AURIX 32-bit SoC using the tpm2-tss library.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] Requires additional libraries (dotnet) to run on Linux.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] These TPM libraries are sometimes also called TPM stacks, because they provide the interface for the developer or user to interact with the TPM.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] As seen from the table, the TPM stacks abstract the operating system and transport layer, so the user could migrate one application between platforms.
[src:secure-firmware-update/trusted-platform-module] For example, by using TPM stack API the user would interact the same way with a TPM, regardless if the physical chip is connected over SPI, I2C or LPC interface to the Host system.
